1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROHIBIT LITIGATION INVESTMENTS IN THE CIVIL JUSTICE SYSTEM,
3 TO PREVENT THE CIVIL JUSTICE SYSTEM FROM BECOMING A FINANCIAL
4 INVESTMENT MARKET, TO AMEND THE WORKERS' COMPENSATION ACT TO
5 INCREASE CERTAIN BENEFITS UNDER THE SCHEDULE OF INJURIES, AND TO
6 PROVIDE FOR AUTOMATIC BENEFIT ADJUSTMENTS BASED UPON INCREASES
7 IN THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX.
8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 PART I. PROHIBIT LITIGATION INVESTMENTS
11 SECTION 1. Chapter 66 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
12 to read:
13 "Article 52.
14 "Prohibit Litigation Investments Act.
15 "§ 66-511. Short title.
16 This Article may be cited as the Prohibit Litigation Investments Act.
17 "§ 66-512. Policy and statement of purpose.
18 (a) It is the policy of this State that the civil justice system function to resolve disputes
19 on the merits between the parties to the proceeding, redress injured parties for civil wrongs,
20 provide consistent and fair treatment to all parties, and, above all, to mete out justice. Legal
21 claims and courthouses in this State are not financial markets for investments and are not vehicles
22 for third parties to profit by financing a party to a civil proceeding for the purpose of obtaining
23 and maximizing an investment return. The civil justice system in this State is not a financial
24 market but is an instrument of justice and must remain distinct from financial markets. The State
25 seeks to facilitate the creation of wealth and economic opportunity for all North Carolinians
26 through a predictable legal climate. It is also the policy of this State to protect our courthouses,
27 judicial system, and national security from hostile foreign actors that participate in litigation
28 investments for improper purposes.
29 The General Assembly finds that litigation investment undermines the civil justice system
30 and threatens national security as follows:
31 (1) Litigation investors invest in legal claims with the goal of returning a profit,
32 undermining the purpose of the legal system to render justice.
33 (2) Litigation investors exert control over claims in which they have invested,
34 undermining the right of claimants to direct the course of their claims.
*H315-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The involvement of litigation investors in proceedings undermines the
2 attorney-client relationship and conflicts with the duties of confidentiality and
3 loyalty that attorneys owe to their clients.
4 (4) Litigation investors unnecessarily prolong proceedings in pursuit of profits
5 and prevent settlement based on non-monetary terms, causing the parties to
6 incur higher costs and wasting judicial resources.
7 (5) Litigation investors' rejection of reasonable settlement offers results in
8 defendants paying a premium to settle cases above what the merits of the claim
9 dictate.
10 (6) Litigation investment presents a threat to national security by allowing
11 undisclosed foreign persons and entities to invest in domestic legal claims. By
12 investing in domestic legal claims, hostile foreign actors are able to impact the
13 integrity of our court system, undermining our self-government, extract
14 resources from economic competitors by requiring them to defend or settle
15 claims beyond what the merits dictate, and obtain sensitive commercial
16 information and intellectual property through the discovery process. North
17 Carolina is home to manufacturing, research, and knowledge-based
18 companies in the technology, aviation, transportation, pharmaceutical health
19 care, agricultural, and other industries that are targets for hostile foreign
20 actors.
21 (7) The threat to national security posed by litigation investment is heightened by
22 the ability of hostile foreign actors to distract American companies in the
23 technology and defense sectors from their missions by financing legal claims
24 against them that require significant resources to defend.
25 (b) It is the purpose of this Article to further the substantive policy set forth in this section,
26 to counteract and prevent the negative consequences of litigation investment as found by the
27 General Assembly, and to maintain the integrity of the civil justice system in this State by broadly
28 prohibiting non-party investment in legal claims and preventing the transformation of the civil
29 justice system into a market for financial investment so that North Carolinians can avail
30 themselves of their right to access the civil justice system free from improper foreign financial
31 influences.
32 "§ 66-513. Definitions.
33 The following definitions apply in this Article:
34 (1) Civil proceeding. – A civil action, arbitration, mediation, administrative
35 proceeding, or other proceeding to resolve a civil legal claim.
36 (2) Immediate family member. – Defined in G.S. 53-244.030.
37 (3) Litigation investment. – The provision of money, whether as a direct payment,
38 advancement, loan, investment, or otherwise, for the fees, costs, and expenses
39 of or related to a pending or potential civil proceeding in exchange for a right
40 to receive repayment or other consideration that is contingent in any respect
41 on the outcome of the pending or potential civil proceeding. The term does
42 not include any of the following:
43 a. The provision of legal services on a contingency basis in accordance
44 with the North Carolina Rules of Professional Conduct.
45 b. An attorney or law firm's advancement of costs and expenses in
46 accordance with the North Carolina Rules of Professional Conduct.
47 c. An insurer or other entity's contractual obligation to indemnify or
48 defend a party to a civil proceeding.
49 d. The provision of money to or by a nonprofit organization for the fees,
50 costs, and expenses of a civil proceeding commenced by the nonprofit
51 organization on behalf of itself or its members so long as any
Page 2 House Bill 315-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 repayment amount is limited to the original amount plus reasonable
2 interest.
3 e. The provision of money to or by a nonprofit legal services organization
4 for the pro bono, cost-free representation of a client in a civil
5 proceeding so long as any repayment amount is limited to the original
6 amount plus reasonable interest.
7 f. A direct loan to a party, law firm, or attorney so long as repayment of
8 the loan is not contingent on the outcome of any civil proceeding.
9 g. The provision of money or other financial support to a party for
10 personal and household expenses during the pendency of a civil
11 proceeding so long as the money or financial support is not used for
12 the fees, costs, and expenses of the civil proceeding.
13 h. The provision of money or other financial support to a party for fees,
14 costs, and expenses of a civil proceeding so long as the source of the
15 money or financial support does not receive a right to any portion of
16 the judgment, settlement, or other monetary relief the party recovers
17 in the civil proceeding or any other right to receive repayment or other
18 consideration that is contingent in any respect on the outcome of the
19 civil proceeding.
20 i. An immediate family member's provision of money or other financial
21 support to a party for fees, costs, and expenses of a civil proceeding or
22 for personal and household expenses during the pendency of a civil
23 proceeding, regardless of whether the immediate family member
24 receives a right to any portion of the judgment, settlement, or other
25 monetary relief the party recovers in the civil proceeding or any other
26 right to receive repayment or other consideration that is contingent in
27 any respect on the outcome of the civil proceeding.
28 "§ 66-514. Prohibition on litigation investment.
29 It is unlawful for a person to engage in litigation investment in this State or to furnish
30 litigation investment to a party or counsel of record in a civil proceeding in this State.
31 "§ 66-515. Enforcement; penalties; remedies.
32 (a) A contract in violation of this Article is void.
33 (b) The Attorney General may bring an action to enjoin violations of this Article. In this
34 action, the court may also impose a civil penalty of up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) for
35 each violation of this Article.
36 (c) A person injured by a violation of this Article may bring an action to recover damages
37 and is entitled to elect at judgment between common law damages as measured by the trier of
38 fact and statutory damages as measured by treble the amount of the full potential litigation
39 investment contemplated by the investor. The injured person is also entitled to an award of court
40 costs and reasonable attorneys' fees.
41 (d) In an action arising under subsection (b) or (c) of this section, a person that has
42 engaged in the business of litigation investment or furnished litigation investment to a party or
43 counsel of record in a civil proceeding in this State has purposefully availed itself of the privileges
44 of conducting business in this State and is subject to suit in this State, whether or not the person
45 is transacting or has transacted any other business in this State. This Article shall be construed as
46 a special jurisdiction statute in accordance with G.S. 1-75.4(2).
47 (e) The remedies and penalties available under this section are in addition to any other
48 remedies provided for by law.
49 "§ 66-516. Construction.
50 This Article shall be liberally construed to effectuate its purpose."
